    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Maven lets you specify either goals or lifecycle phases on the command line (or both).</p>\n<p><code>clean</code> and <code>install</code> are <a href=\"http://maven.apache.org/guides/introduction/introduction-to-the-lifecycle.html#Lifecycle_Reference\" rel=\"noreferrer\">two different phases of two different lifecycles</a>, to which <a href=\"http://maven.apache.org/guides/introduction/introduction-to-the-lifecycle.html#Built-in_Lifecycle_Bindings\" rel=\"noreferrer\">different plugin goals are bound</a> (either per default or <a href=\"http://maven.apache.org/guides/introduction/introduction-to-the-lifecycle.html#Plugins\" rel=\"noreferrer\">explicitly in your pom.xml</a>)</p>\n<p>The <code>clean</code> phase, per convention, is meant to make a build reproducible, i.e. it cleans up anything that was created by previous builds. In most cases it does that by calling <a href=\"http://maven.apache.org/plugins/maven-clean-plugin/clean-mojo.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>clean:clean</code></a>, which deletes the directory bound to <code>${project.build.directory}</code> (usually called &quot;target&quot;)</p>\n"
  }, {
